               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18451027-name-592" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-592" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-592" type="surname" value="ROBSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18451027-name-592" type="given" value="JOHN WORDSWORTH"></interp>JOHN WORDSWORTH ROBSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an artist, and live at Wapping-Wall. The prisoner came into my service about fifteen weeks before my wife's death, which was on the 24th Sept., and continued so since—I missed some articles after my wife's death, and spoke to the prisoner about it—she offered to swear on the Bible that she had not made away with any of my property—on the 10th of Oct. I went to Mr. Williams, a pawnbroker in New Gravel-lane, and there found this shift and pet<lb></lb>ticoat, and a pair of shoes, which are mine—I gave her into custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> The shoes are mine, and the other things I was ordered to pledge by his wife. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> I bought the shoes myself for my wife, and am sure of them—a quantity of property was pawned before my wife's death, which I have not indicted her for; but these were pledged on the 9th of Oct., and my wife died on the 24th of Sept.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
